<p>The International Chess Federation (FIDE) said it will examine public statements by former world champion Vladimir Kramnik after the recent death of American grandmaster Daniel Naroditsky, who died at age 29 [aljazeera.com#1][euronews.com#1][abc.net.au#1]. Reports say Kramnik repeatedly accused Naroditsky of cheating during the year before his death; those allegations are described in coverage as unproven [aljazeera.com#1][cbsnews.com#1]. FIDE’s review could lead to disciplinary action under its rules, a move that highlights growing institutional attention to harassment and unverified public accusations in chess [abc.net.au#1][cbsnews.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/0GeB2t0Ydy6JGAlIV-EI-R7zO46Ne7Wh0fb4Dps33iGrjWRQv-GvdL2pGfyQSxD1Ors-J0kW5NRBaan628mdoPFio2bITaUrMTrnGeQq3_okp9zEuSY8-qIT5nJhiyktM5ujn7Lty4iOh-ptkmgHCkbn1zrgiq_PvRzk4WWc24SV9SHMtHAv9iTasUr2g7KnqNyWy8MYesh_7JRas22Xzv-doo_Sdk0Ip-k-t0o5X421W5W2PTBTo7PPZw' alt='Statements made by Russian chess champion Vladimir Kramnik will be reviewed following the death of Daniel Naroditsky.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>FIDE statement: FIDE said it will review Kramnik’s public remarks and decide whether to open formal disciplinary proceedings, but it did not announce immediate sanctions [abc.net.au#1][euronews.com#1]</li><li>Pattern of accusations: Multiple reports detail that Kramnik repeatedly levelled cheating allegations against Naroditsky across the past year, increasing scrutiny of the younger player before his death [aljazeera.com#1][cbsnews.com#1]</li><li>Discipline possible: Media coverage notes FIDE may discipline a titled player for misconduct or harassment if an investigation finds breaches of its rules [cbsnews.com#1]</li><li>Broader debate: The case has renewed discussion about how chess institutions and platforms should handle public accusations and the need for evidence-based processes [aljazeera.com#1]</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>FIDE (International Chess Federation): FI